The values of a function $f(x)$ are given below:

\begin{tabular}{|c||c|c|c|c|c|} \hline $x$ & 3 & 4 & 5 & 6 & 7 \\ \hline $f(x)$ & 10 & 17 & 26 & 37 & 50 \\ \hline \end{tabular}Evaluate $f^{-1}\left(f^{-1}(50)\times f^{-1}(10)+f^{-1}(26)\right)$.
inference:
The value of the function's inverse at $50$, denoted as $f^{-1}(50)$, is the input value that corresponds to an output value of $50$. Looking at the table, we find that this is $x=7$.
$$f^{-1}(50)=7$$Similarly, the value of the function's inverse at $10$, denoted as $f^{-1}(10)$, is 3 and the value of the function's inverse at $26$, denoted as $f^{-1}(26)$, is 5.
$$f^{-1}(10)=3$$
$$f^{-1}(26)=5$$Thus,
$$f^{-1}\left(f^{-1}(50) \cdot f^{-1}(10) + f^{-1}(26)\right)=f^{-1}\left(7 \cdot 3 + 5\right)=f^{-1}\left(26\right)=\boxed{5}$$
Final Answer: \boxed{$5$}. I hope it is correct.
